          "body": "The chapter closes with a movement that would be impossible to fabricate from the outside: Job is genuinely terrified of God (23:15-16) and he refuses to be silenced (23:17) — in the same breath. Verse 15 names the terror: 'I would be dismayed at His presence; when I consider, I am terrified of Him.' Verse 16 goes further: 'It is God who has made my heart faint, and the Almighty who has dismayed me' — the very God Job longed to find (23:3) is the author of the terror Job feels at the prospect of finding Him. The sovereignty of 23:13-14 has produced not comfort but awe that shades into dread. God is fully in control; that is the terrifying datum. And yet verse 17's closing adversative — 'But I am not silenced by the darkness, nor the deep gloom which covers me' — refuses the silence the darkness demands. Job will keep speaking. He will keep complaining. He will not mistake terror for abandonment or divine sovereignty for divine indifference. The refusal to be silenced (tsamat, to be cut off, extinguished) is itself an act of faith — not the triumphant faith of Psalm 46, but the bruised, clinging, defiant faith of a man who has looked in every direction, found darkness, and opened his mouth anyway. Calvin called this the 'wrestling of faith' — where the soul cries out not because it doubts God's existence but because it clings to the God whose face it cannot see."
